text: World J Microbiol Biotechnol (2017) 33:126  DOI 10.1007/s11274-017-2292-8 Isolation, purification and chemical characterization of a new  angucyclinone compound produced by a new halotolerant  Nocardiopsis sp. HR-4 strain Yamina Hadj Rabia-Boukhalfa1,2,3 · Yannick Eveno3 · Solange Karama2 ·  Okba Selama1 · Béatrice Lauga2 · Robert Duran2 · Hocine Hacène1 ·  Véronique Eparvier3  Received: 25 January 2017 / Accepted: 20 May 2017 / Published online: 25 May 2017  © Springer Science+Business Media Dordrecht 2017 Abstract  A  halotolerant  Actinobacteria  strain  HR-4  was  isolated  from  a  salt  lake  soil  sample  in  Algerian  Sahara.  Analysis  of  16S  rDNA  gene  sequence  showed  that  strain  HR-4  belonged  to  the  genus  Nocardiopsis.  The  similarity  level  ranges  between  97.45  and  99.20%  with  Nocardiop- sis species and Nocardiopsis rosea being the most closely  related  one.  Morphological,  physiological  and  phyloge- netic  characteristics  comparisons  showed  significant  dif- ferences  with  the  nearest  species.  These  data  strongly  suggest  that  strain  HR-4  represents  novel  species.  The  antimicrobial activity of strain HR-4 showed an antibacte- rial  activity  against  Gram-positive  bacteria  as  well  as  an  antifungal  one.  Two  major  natural  products  including  a  new  one  were  isolated  from  the  culture  broth  using  vari- ous  separation  and  purification  procedures.  The  chemical  structure  established  on  the  basis  of  spectroscopic  studies

Electronic supplementary material  The online version of this  article (doi:10.1007/s11274-017-2292-8) contains supplementary  material, which is available to authorized users. 1  Equipe Microbiologie, Laboratoire de Biologie Cellulaire et  Moléculaire, Faculté des Sciences Biologique-Université des  Sciences et de la Technologie Houari Boumediene, BP 32, El  Alia, 16111 Bab Ezzouar Alger, Algeria 2  Equipe Environnement et Microbiologie, Institut  3  CNRS – Institut de Chimie des Substances Naturelles  Pluridisciplinaire de Recherche sur l’Environnement et les  Matériaux, UMR 5254, Centre national de la recherche  scientifique-Université de Pau et des Pays de l’Adour, Pau,  France - Equipe Métabolites de Microorganismes Symbiotiques-Bi oinspiration, 1 Avenue de la Terrasse, 91198 Gif-sur-Yvette,  France NMR and by comparing with spectroscopic data from the  literature of the two compounds affirm that they are classi- fied in the group of Angucyclinones. This is the first report  of  a  production  of  this  type  of  molecules  by  the  genus  Nocardiopsis. The new natural compound was established  as  (−)-7-deoxy-8-O-methyltetrangomycin  with  a  new  configuration. Keywords  Halotolerant · Nocardiopsis · Taxonomy ·  Antimicrobial activity · Angucyclinone

Actinobacteria  are  the  most  important  group  of  microor- ganisms for the production of antibiotics and other impor- tant  natural  substances  (Berdy  2005;  Barka  et  al.  2016).  The most frequent producers in this group, the Streptomy- ces  species  produce  7600  compounds  (74%),  while  other  Actinobacteria represent (26%) altogether 2500 compounds  (Ilic et al. 2007). In the course of screening for new active  molecules,  several  research  studies  are  currently  oriented  towards isolation of rare and unusual genera of Actinobac- teria from different ecosystems and particularly from halo- philic soils (Hacène et al. 1994, 2004; Lazzarini et al. 2001;  Cai 2009; Hamedi et al. 2013). Nocardiopsis  species  are  generally  associated  with  Saharan  soils.  Different  types  of  soil  samples  (saline  and  hypersaline  desert)  have  yielded  several  novel  iso- lates.  The  most  striking  feature  of  these  isolates  is  their  requirement  for  NaCl  or  tolerance  toward  it  (Hamedi  et  al.  2013;  Bennur  et  al. 2015).  Members  of  this  genus  produce an array of natural products like: enzymes, com- patible solutes, surfactants and bioactive compounds that  may  aid  their  survival  under  extremophilic  conditions  (Li et al. 2013; Bennur et al. 2014). In fact, Nocardiopsis  species  harbor  different  types  of  PKS  gene  clusters  that  help them in producing of large kinds of natural products  (Becerril-Espinosa et al. 2013; Romanenko et al. 2013).

Our  laboratory  takes  a  particular  interest  in  extreme  environments  and  drug  discovery,  and  many  new  gen- era, species and substances were described (Hacène et al.  1994, 1998, 2000; Addou et al. 2012, 2013). In  the  present  work,  we  describe  the  identification  of  a  halotolerant  Nocardiopsis  strain  designated  HR-4  iso- lated from a salt Saharan soil sample by conventional and  molecular methods. Also, we report the extraction, puri- fication and structure elucidation of the new major natu- ral  product  from  liquid  culture  broth  of  this  strain,  and  for  the  first  time  the  production  of  angucyclinones  com- pounds by Nocardiopsis species. The  Actinobacteria  strain  designated  HR-4  was  isolated  from  an  Algerian  salt  lake  soil  named  Sebkha  of  Ain  Salah  located  in  Sahara  desert.  A  dry  subsample  soil  (1 g) was suspended in sterile distilled water and decimal  diluted to  10−4. Aliquots (0.2 mL) of each dilution were  spread  on  to  International  Streptomyces  Project  2  (ISP  2)  medium  agar  supplemented  with  10%  of  NaCl  (w/v)  (Shirling  and  Gottlieb  1966).  The  medium  was  supple- mented  with  gentamycin  (10  µg/L)  and  amphotericin  B  (50 µg/L) to inhibit the growth of the other bacteria and  fungi respectively. The plates were incubated at 30 °C for  2 weeks. Morphological and cultural characterization

The  morphological  and  cultural  features  were  observed  by  naked-eye  examination  of  14  day-old  cultures  grown  on  various  International  Streptomyces  Project  (ISP)  media:  tryptone  yeast  extract  agar  (ISP  1),  yeast  extract–malt  extract  agar  (ISP  2),  inorganic  salts–starch  agar (ISP 4) and glycerol–asparagine agar (ISP 5) (Shirl- ing  and  Gottlieb  1966).  All  media  were  supplemented  with 10% of NaCl (w/v) and incubated at 30 °C. The  micromorphology  and  sporulation  were  observed  by  light  microscopy  (B1  Series,  Motic  Gx1000).  Colors  of aerial and substrate mycelia and any soluble pigments  produced were also determined with the ISCC-NBS color  charts (Kelly and Judd 1976). Physiological characterization Production  of  melanoid  pigments  was  tested  on  tyrosine  agar  (ISP  7)  medium  (Shirling  and  Gottlieb  1966).  The  assimilation  of  carbohydrate  as  sole  carbon  source  was  determined on ISP 9 medium (Shirling and Gottlieb 1966).  Degradation of starch, casein, gelatine and nitrate reductase  production were determined as described by Locci (1989). Growth at different NaCl concentrations (0, 5, 10, 15, 20  and 25%) and different temperatures (20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45,  50  and  55 °C)  were  evaluated  on  ISP  2  medium.  The  pH  range of growth was investigated between (4.0 and 12.0 at  intervals of 1 pH unit) on ISP 2 agar medium supplemented  with 10% of NaCl and incubated at 30 °C for 14 days. DNA Extraction, 16S rDNA sequencing,  and phylogenetic analysis

DNA was extracted using the Ultra Clean Microbial DNA  Isolation  kit  (MO  BIO  Laboratories,  Carlsbad,  CA).  The  strain of Actinobacteria was grown at 30 °C for 7 days with  agitation  (250  rpm)  in  a  250  mL  flask  containing  50  mL  of  ISP  2  liquid  medium  supplemented  with  10%  of  NaCl.  The  16S  rDNA  was  amplified  by  PCR  using  two  primers  (Eurogentec,  Seraing,  Belgium):  63F  (5′-AGT GAG CCC  TGA AAA TCA TGG ACT -3′)  and  1387R  (5′-GGG CGG  WGTG TAC AAGGC-3′).  The  final  50-µL  volume  of  reac- tion  mixture  contained  Amplitaq  Gold  DNA  Master  Mix  2 X (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA, USA) (Ampli- Taq Gold DNA Polymerase, 250 U (0.05 U/μL), GeneAmp  PCR Gold Buffer, 30 mM Tris/HCl, pH 8.05, 100 mM KCl,  dNTP  400  μM  each,  5  mM   MgCl2),  sterile  water,  20  µM  of each primer and 5 µL of the purified DNA. PCR ampli- fication of the 16 rDNA was carried out on M J Research  PTC-200  Thermal  Cycler  (Waltham,  MA,  USA).  The  conditions  for  thermal  cycling  were  as  follows:  denatura- tion of the target DNA at 95 °C for 10 min followed by 35  cycles of 95 °C for 45S, primer annealing at 55 °C for 45S  and primer extension at 72 °C for 1 min. At the end of the  cycling, the reaction mixture was held at 72 °C for 10 min  and then cooled to 4 °C. The PCR product was

annealing at 55 °C for 45S  and primer extension at 72 °C for 1 min. At the end of the  cycling, the reaction mixture was held at 72 °C for 10 min  and then cooled to 4 °C. The PCR product was detected by  agarose 1% gel electrophoresis and was visualized by ultra- violet (UV) fluorescence after ethidium bromide staining.

The  obtained  16S  rDNA  gene  sequence  of  strain  HR-4  was  compared  for  similarity  level  with  sequences  present  in the public sequence (NCBI Genbank) databases as well  as in the EzTaxon-e server (Kim et al. 2012). Phylogenetic  analyses  were  realized  using  MEGA  version  6  developed  by  Tamura  et  al.  (2013).  The  multiple  alignment  of  the  obtained  16S  rDNA  gene  sequence  against  neighbour- ing  nucleotide  sequences,  recovered  from  EzTaxon,  was  generated  using  CLUSTAL  W  (with  default  parameters)  (Thompson  et  al.  1994).  The  phylogenetic  trees  were  World J Microbiol Biotechnol (2017) 33:126 World J Microbiol Biotechnol (2017) 33:126  constructed  using  several  algorithms:  the  neighbour-join- ing  method  of  Saitou  and  Nei  (1987)  with  the  model  of  Jukes and Cantor (1969), maximum-likelihood (Felsenstein  1981) with Kimura’s two-parameter model (Kimura 1980)  and  maximum-parsimony  (Fitch  1977).  Tree  topologies  were evaluated using the bootstrap resampling method with  1000 replicates (Felsenstein 1985). Screening of antimicrobial activity Antimicrobial assay on solid medium The antagonistic properties of the isolate HR-4 against sev- eral bacteria and filamentous fungi were determined by the  cylinder  agar  plate  method  of  ISP  2  medium  containing  10% NaCl.

The following strains of bacteria and fungi were used: Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 25923, Methicillin-Resist- ant  Staphylococcus  aureus  (MRSA)  ATCC  43300,  Micro- coccus  luteus  ATCC  4698,  Enterococcus  faecalis,  ATCC  29212,  Escherichia  coli  ATCC  25922,  Pseudomonas  aer- uginosa  ATCC  27853,  Saccharomyces  cerevisiae  ATCC  9763, Candida albicans ATCC 10231 from American Type  of Culture Collection (Manassas, VA, USA) and Fusarium  oxysporum  DSM   62297T  from  Deutsche  Sammlung  von  Mikroorganismen und Zellkulturen DSMZ (Braunschweig,  Germany). Time course of growth and antibiotic production Fermentation  of  strain  HR-4  was  carried  in  order  to  select  the  culture  time  favourable  for  antibiotic  produc- tion. 500 mL Erlenmeyer flasks containing 100 mL of ISP  2  broth  medium  supplemented  with  10%  of  NaCl  were  inoculated  with  3  mL  of  2  days  pre-culture.  The  cultures  were run at 30 °C for 10 days under agitation at 200 rpm.  Changes in pH, growth (dry weight of mycelium) and anti- biotic  production  were  examined  daily.  The  antimicrobial  activity in the culture broth was monitored by the conven- tional agar diffusion assay (well technique) using Staphylo- coccus  aureus  ATCC  25923  and  Candida  albicans.  Each  6  mm  diameter  well  was  filled  with  250  µL  of  culture  supernatant. Detection of PKS I, PKSII and NRPS genes

Genomic  potential  for  producing  bioactive  metabolites  of  the  isolate  was  evaluated  by  using  specific  degener- ate  primers  (Eurogentec,  Seraing,  Belgium).  Polyketide  synthetase  I  (PKS-I),  and  Non  Ribosomal  Peptide  Syn- thetase (NRPS) genes were amplified from genomic DNA  ′ with the primer pairs K1F/M6R  (5 -TSAAGTCSAAC ATC  ′ ′ ′ )  and  -CGC AGG TTSCSGTA CCA GTA-3  5 ;  GGBCA-3 ′ ′ A3F/A7R  -GCSTACSYSATSTACA  CSTCSGG-3 ;  ′ ′ ),  respectively,  accord- -SASGTCVCCSGTSCGGTAS-3  5 ing  to  Ayuso-Sacido  and  Genilloud  (2005).  Polyketide  synthetase II (PKS-II) gene was amplified with the primer  ′ ′ pair  KS  α/KS  β   (5 ;  -TSGCSTGC TTG GAYGC  SATC-3 ′ ′ ),  as  described  by  -TGGAANCCG CCG AABCCTCT-3  5 Metsä-Ketelä et al. (1999). The reaction mixtures contained  AmpliTaq  Gold  Master  Mix  2X,  sterile  water,  20  µM  of  each primer and 5 µL of the purified DNA in a 50 µL reac- tion volume. Control reaction mixture had no Actinobacte- rial DNA template.

Thermocycling  conditions  for  K1F/M6R  and  KS  α/KS  β consisted of one denaturation step of 5 min at 95 °C; 35  amplification  cycles  of  30  s  at  95 °C,  2  min  at  55 °C  for  K1F/M6R or 2 min at 58 °C for KS α/KS β, 4 min at 72 °C;  and a final extension for 10 min at 72 °C. Thermocycling  conditions  for  A3F/A7R  consisted  of  one  denaturation  step  of  5  min  at  94 °C;  30  amplification  cycles of 1 min at 94 °C, 1 min at 57 °C, and 2 min at 72 °C;  and  a  final  extension  for  5  min  at  72 °C  as  described  by  Sheng et al. (2009). The  strain  was  cultivated  in  ISP2  liquid  medium  supple- mented with 10% of NaCl at 30 °C for 8 days. The culture  broth  (8.0  L  was  extracted  with  an  equal  volume  of  Ethyl  acetate (EtOAc) for 24 h. The organic solvent was then col- lected by filtration, washed with  H2O in a separatory fun- nel, and evaporated, yielding 34 mg of the extract. Isolation and purification of natural compounds

Analytical  and  preparative  HPLCs  were  conducted  with  a  Gilson  system  (Middleton,  WI,  USA)  equipped  with  a  322  pumping  device,  a  GX-271  fraction  collector,  a  171  diode  array  detector  and  a  prepELSII  detector  elec- trospray  nebuliser.  Columns  used  for  these  experiments  included:  a  Phenomenex  (Torrance,  CA,  USA)  Luna   C18  5 µm 4.6 × 250 mm, Phenomenex PFP 5 µm 4.6 × 250 mm  analytical  column  and  Phenomenex  Luna   C18  5  µm  21.2 × 250  mm  and  PFP  5  µm  21.5 × 250  mm  preparative  column. The flow rate was set to 1 or 17 mL/min, respec- tively,  using  a  linear  gradient  of  water  mixed  with  an  increasing proportion of acetonitrile  (CH3CN). All solvents  were HPLC grade. All  of  the  amplification  products  were  examined  with  1%  agarose  gel  electrophoresis,  and  bands  of  1200–1400,  600 and 800 bp were classified as products of PKS I, PKS  II and NRPS genes respectively. Production, isolation and characterisation of natural  products Fermentation and preparation of crude extract

Nuclear  Magnetic  Resonance  (NMR)  spectra  were  recorded on a Bruker (Fremont, CA, USA) 500 MHz spec- trometer  equipped  with  a  1  mm  inverse  detection  probe.  Chemical  shifts  (δ)  are  reported  as  ppm  based  on  TMS  signal,  and  coupling  constants  (J)  are  reported  in  Hertz.  HR-ESI-MS measurements were performed using a Waters  Acquity  UPLC  system  (Milford,  MA,  USA)  with  column  bypass coupled to a Waters Micromass LCT Premier Time- of-Flight mass spectrometer (Milford, MA, USA) equipped  with an electrospray interface (ESI). Flash chromatography  was  performed  on  a  Grace  Reveleris  system  (Columbia,  MD,  USA)  with  dual  UV  and  ELSD  detection  equipped  with  an  80  g  silica  column.  For  UV-based  experiments,  effluents were monitored at 254 and 280 nm. Optical  rotations  were  measured  on  an  Anton  Paar  (Graz,  Austria)  MCP  300  polarimeter  in  a  100  mm-long  350 µL cells. Biological assays of purified compounds

The disk diffusion assay was used to test the antimicrobial  activities  of  the  purified  compounds.  Methanol  (MeOH)  was  used  to  dissolve  each  pure  compound  and  100  μL  of  the  compound  solution  (representing  50  μg)  were  applied  to  6.0  mm  paper  disk.  The  disk  was  allowed  to  dry  for  1  h  before  it  was  placed  on  the  plate  inoculated  with  the  target  microorganisms  (bacterial  strains  and  C.  albicans  used above). The plates were incubated at 37 and 30 °C for  bacteria and C. albicans respectively. The diameter of the  inhibition zone (mm) of each active compound was meas- ured after 24 and 48 h for bacteria and  yeast  respectively.  Disks treated with 100 μL of MeOH were used as negative  controls. The cultural and morphological characteristics of the strain  in  different  media  are  given  in  Table  1.  The  strain  HR-4  showed  an  excellent  growth  and  abundant  aerial  myce- lium formation on ISP 2 supplemented with 10% of NaCl.  Good  growth  was  observed  on  yeast  extract  agar  whereas  Table 1   Culture characteristics  of strain HR-4 on various media Tryptone yeast extract agar ISP 1 Yeast malt extract agar ISP 2 Inorganic salt-starch agar ISP 4 Glycerol-asparagin agar ISP 5 Tyrosin agar ISP7

only  moderate  growth  was  seen  on  Asparagin  agar  ISP  5  and  Tyrosin  agar  ISP  7  and  poor  growth  was  detected  on  inorganic salt agar ISP 4. The color of substrate mycelium  was light brown on ISP 1, strong yellowish brown on ISP 2,  white on ISP 4 and light brown on ISP 5 and ISP 7. Yeast  extract malt extract agar ISP 2 supplemented with 10% of  NaCl  was  used  as  the  optimal  medium  for  the  culture  of  the strain. Substrate and aerial mycelia are well developed  and the latter fragments into spores which were non motile  (Fig. 1). The  physiological  properties  of  strain  HR-4  (Table  2)  showed  that  no  melanoid  pigments  were  produced  on  the  used  media,  and  the  isolate  used  the  following  as  carbon  sources:  glucose,  sucrose,  cellulose,  lactose,  xylose,  man- nitol  and  inositol  but  it  was  not  able  to  use  rhamnose,  melobiose  and  arabinose.  It  was  found  to  be  positive  for  production of catalase and gelatinase and was found to be  negative  for  the  production  of  nitrate  reductase,  amylase  and caseinase. The  similarity  analysis  based  on  16S  rDNA  sequence  (1239  bp)  of  strain  HR-4,  deposited  in  GenBank  under  accession number KC511627, indicated that the strain was  closely  related  to  members  of  genus  Nocardiopsis  (Meyer  1976)  and  was  closely  related  to  N.  rosea  DSM   44842T  (99.20%),  N.  gilva  DSM   44841T  (98.72%),  N.  rhodophea  DSM   44843T  (98.40%)  (Li  et  al.  2006)  and  N.  halophila  DSM  44494T (97.77%) (Al-Tai and Ruan 1994). This asso- ciation was supported by the maximum likelihood dendro- gram  (Fig.  2).  Strain  HR-4  could  be  distinguished  from  the  closely  species  by  some  phenotypic  properties  like:  Color of aerial and substrate mycelia, Gelatin liquefaction,  Nitrate reduction and the utilization of Mannose and Fruc- tose (Table 3). Nocardiopsis sp. HR-4 showed a broad antimicrobial activ- ity spectrum which is presented in Table 4. The strain HR-4 exhibited a variety of antibacterial and  antifungal activity. It showed a good activity against Gram- positive  bacteria  such  as  the  two  strains  of  S.  aureus,  E.  faecalis and M. luteus. However, no activity against Gram- negative  bacteria  was  observed.  Also,  the  strain  HR-4  showed  a  good  activity  against  S.  cerevisiae  and  C.  albi- cans but a weak activity was observed on F. oxysporum.

The isolate was screened for the presence of PKS I, PKS  II, and NRPS sequences by specific amplification of chro- mosomal DNA with primer sets K1F/M6R,  KSα/KSβ, and  A3F/A7R,  respectively,  to  evaluate  its  biosynthetic  poten- tial  in  terms  of  natural  compounds  production.  The  strain  harbored the PKS I, PKS II and NRPS genes. These genes  are  established  to  be  associated  with  a  diversity  of  bioac- tive natural products (Ayuso-Sacido et al. 2005). Time course of growth and antimicrobial production The  kinetics  of  antimicrobial  production,  growth  and  pH  were monitored in ISP 2 broth cultures with 10% of NaCl  as shown in the (Fig. 3). The activities were detected on the  first  day  of  fermentation  against  S.  aureus  ATCC  25923,  and on the second day against C. albicans, reaching a max- imum the 8th day. The biomass increased from the first day  to the 8th day, and then decreased after the 9th day. The pH  kinetics showed slight variation during the incubation. Isolation and purification of natural product The  8.0  L  shake  flasks  culture  was  extracted  at  room  temperature by maceration using EtOAc; the residue was  subsequently extracted using the same volume of EtOAc  providing 34 mg of extract, after evaporation of the sol- vents,  which  corresponds  to  a  yield  of  7.9 × 10−5  mg/g

On  the  basis  of  its  morphological  physiological  and  phy- logenetic  characteristics  described  above,  the  strain  HR-4  was  classified  in  the  genus  Nocardiopsis.  Strain  HR-4  could be distinguished from the related species by pheno- typic  properties,  such  as  the  color  of  aerial  and  substrate  mycelia, indeed the aerial mycelium of strain HR-4 on ISP  2 medium was greyish brown but that of N. rosea was pale  pink and that of N. gilva was pale yellow. Besides, the sub- strate mycelium is dark brown for HR-4, moderate pink for  N. rosea and brillant yellow for N. gilva. Also, on the phys- iological  level,  the  strain  HR-4  differs  by  the  temperature  range growth. The 16S rDNA gene sequence of strain HR-4 was com- pared with those of other Nocardiopsis species. The simi- larity level ranged from 97.45 to 99.20%, N. rosea (Li et al.  2006)  being  the  most  closely  related  species.  However,  it  is clear from phylogenetic analysis that strain HR-4 repre- sents a distinct phyletic line suggesting a new species of the  genus Nocardiopsis. Diameter of inhibition  zones (mm)

It is well known that certain bacterial and fungal genera  produce antibiotics as part of their metabolism (Waksman  et  al.  2010).  These  substances  are  mainly  secreted  against  competing micro-organisms and to ensure restricted use of  solubilized nutrients (Chater 2006). They also act as molec- ular signals and mediate cellular communication and gene  transfer  phenoma  (Davies  2006;  Linares  et  al.  2006).  So,  they  play  a  significant  role  in  structuring  microbial  com- munities  (Tarkka  et  al.  2008).  Members  of  genus  Nocar- diopsis also produce a wide array of antimicrobial agents.  Screening  of  samples  for  Actinobacteria  producing  bioac- tive  compounds  have  yielded  Nocardiopsis  species  along  with  other  bacteria  (Vimal  et  al.  2009;  Augustine  et  al.  2012; Romanenko et al. 2013). There are many reports on  the  production  and  detailed  chemical  characterization  of  a  range  of  antibiotics  by  different  species  of  Nocardiop- sis like Polyketides (Li et al. 2013), Phenazine derivatives  (Dashti et al. 2014) and other chemically distinct antimicro- bial compounds (Tian et al. 2013, 2014). The two major compounds were purified by HPLC and  on the basis of NMR and HRESI-MS analysis, the molecu- lar formula were determined as  C20H16O5 for compound 1  and  C20H18O5 for compound 2. The  structure  and  configuration  of  compound  1  were  confirmed  by  comparison  of  spectroscopic  data  with  the  literature values as (−)-8-O-methyltetrangomycin based on  optical  rotation  ([α]23 D = −92  (c  0.1,  MeOH))  (Kesenhe- imer et al. 2010).

The  structure  of  compound  2  was  identified  by  com- parison  with  spectroscopic  data  of  the  literature  as  7-deoxo-6-deoxy-7-hydroxy-8-O -methylrabelomy- cin  (Fotso  et  al.  2008).  But  contrary  to  the  described  compound,  optical  rotation  for  compound  2  is  nega- tive  ([α]23 D  =  −10  (c  0.1,  MeOH)),  which  indicated  that  compound  2  is  a  new  molecule  and  it  was  named  (−)-7-deoxy-8-O-methyltetrangomycin. The  carbons  of  molecules  1  and  2  are  identical  in  the  region of C-1 to C-4 and are perfectly compatible. There- fore,  1  and  2  should  have  the  same  C-3  configuration.  In  addition,  7-deoxo-6-deoxy-7-hydroxy-8-O-methylrabelo- mycin  is  obtained  by  reduction  of  (−)-6-deoxy-8-O-meth- ylrabelomycin;  so  we  have  isolated  different  compound  from the one described by Fotso et al. (2008). The data relative to chemical revelations suggested that  the  two  compounds  purified  are  related  to  the  angucy- clinone  family.  To  our  knowledge,  it  is  the  first  report  of  angucyclinones  isolated  from  Nocardiopsis  species  and  from halotolerant Nocardiopsis. Angucyclinones  and  angucylines  are  aromatic  polyke- tide natural products with a tetracyclic benz[a] anthracene  skeleton  that  is  distinct  from  benz[b]  anthracene  skeleton  found in tetracyclines and anthracyclines. They are biosyn- thesized by type II polyketide synthases. Since the isolation

World J Microbiol Biotechnol (2017) 33:126 World J Microbiol Biotechnol (2017) 33:126  of  tetrangomycin,  the  first  angucyclinone  discovered  from  Streptomyces rimosus in 1965 (Rohr and Thiericke 1992),  the angucycline and angucyclinone family of natural prod- ucts  has  grown  steadily.  To  date,  this  family  of  natural  products has been discovered exclusively from Actinobac- teria,  with  Streptomyces  as  the  major  producers  but  never  from  known  Nocardiopsis  species  (Rohr  and  Thiericke  1992; Kharel et al. 2012). Angucyclines  and  angucyclinones  are  known  for  their  cytotoxicity  and  antibacterial  activities,  and  selectively  inhibit  Gram-positive  bacteria  (Okazaki  et  al.  1975;  The- riault et al. 1986; Rohr and Thiericke 1992; Kalinovskaya  et al. 2008; Jakeman et al. 2009; Igarashi et al. 2013); this  information  was  confirmed  by  antimicrobial  tests  of  the  two compounds isolated in our study.

Nocardiopsis  species  have  been  reported  to  produce  Trehalosamine (Dolak et al. 1980), Polyamine dopsisamine  (Takahashi et al. 1986), 87 kDa protein (Selvin et al. 2009),  Thiopepetide (Engelhardt et al. 2010), Pyrones derivatives  (Fu et al. 2011; Ding et al. 2012; Wang et al. 2013; Komaki  et al. 2014), Phenazine derivatives (Lu et al. 2013), p-Ter- phenyl  derivatives  (Tian  et  al.  2013)  and  Quinolone  alka- loid (Tian et al. 2014). In  conclusion,  the  results  obtained  in  this  study  show  the  production  of  angucyclinone  product  for  the  first  time  by Nocardiopsis species and particularly, the isolation and  characterization  of  a  new  natural  compound  with  a  new  configuration.
